on, 04 Sep 2023 19:06:35 +0000</pubDate></item><item><title>Andrew Plested</title><link>https://mstdn.science/@andrewplested/111007622377858058</link><description>Iva Luƒçiƒá shows our students how to label CaMKII with fluorescent dye for &lt;a class="mention hashtag" href="https://mstdn.science/tags/singleMolecule" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank"&gt;#&lt;span&gt;singleMolecule&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt; TIRF &lt;a class="mention hashtag" href="https://mstdn.science/tags/microscopy" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank"&gt;#&lt;span&gt;microscopy&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a class="mention hashtag" href="https://mstdn.science/tags/biophysics" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank"&gt;#&lt;span&gt;biophysics&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;a href="https://files.mastodon.social/cache/media_attachments/files/111/007/622/512/555/716/original/9f6f3c34b026ed7c.jpeg"&gt;&lt;img src="https://files.mastodon.social/cache/media_attachments/files/111/007/622/512/555/716/original/9f6f3c34b026ed7c.jpeg" alt="Mastodon image" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;</description><guid isPermaLink="false">111008706800809491</guid><pubDate>Mon, 04 Sep 2023 20:14:00 +0000</pubDate></item><item><title>David Colquhoun</title><link>https://mstdn.social/@david_colquhoun/111006592206452740</link><description>"Don‚Äôt believe HR‚Äôs endless blather about ‚Äúputting people first‚Äù or ‚Äúbreaking the silence about bullying‚Äù. It is just spin to enable your university to look good and get its Athena SWAN badge."&lt;br/&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.timeshighereducation.com/opinion/bullying-feature-uk-research-universities-not-bug" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank"&gt;&lt;span class="invisible"&gt;https://www.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="ellipsis"&gt;timeshighereducation.com/opini&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="invisible"&gt;on/bullying-feature-uk-research-universities-not-bug&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;</description><guid isPermaLink="false">111008709509095072</guid><pubDate>Mon, 04 Sep 2023 20:14:42 +0000</pubDate></item><item><title>Gualtiero Piccinini üá∫üá¶</title><link>https://mstdn.social/@Gualtiero/111008879215239434</link><description>In this great paper (which I just discovered), Bryce Huebner augments the Sellarsian distinction between picturing and signifying with affect/evaluation and attention, a useful step towards a more adequate account of neural/mental representation.Picturing, signifying, and attending &lt;a href="https://scindeks.ceon.rs/Article.aspx?artid=0353-38911831007H" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank"&gt;&lt;span class="invisible"&gt;https://&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="ellipsis"&gt;scindeks.ceon.rs/Article.aspx?&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="invisible"&gt;artid=0353-38911831007H&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;</description><guid isPermaLink="false">111008914968781991</guid><pubDate>Mon, 04 Sep 2023 21:06:53 +0000</pubDate></item><item><title>Carl Zimmer</title><link>https://mastodon.social/@Carl_Zimmer/111008998317649272</link><description>New report gauges the huge impact of invasive species on biodiversity, along with a massive economic toll. &lt;a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/09/04/climate/invasive-species-cost-ipbes.html" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" translate="no"&gt;&lt;span class="invisible"&gt;https://www.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="ellipsis"&gt;nytimes.com/2023/09/04/climate&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="invisible"&gt;/invasive-species-cost-ipbes.html&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;</description><guid isPermaLink="false">111008998317649272</guid><pubDate>Mon, 04 Sep 2023 21:28:09 +0000</pubDate></item><item><title>Emeritus Prof Christopher May</title><link>https://zirk.us/@ChrisMayLA6/111011011602388697</link><description>When &lt;a class="mention hashtag" href="https://zirk.us/tags/computers" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank"&gt;#&lt;span&gt;computers&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt; were a little larger than they are todayPhotographer Berenice Abbott, 'Woman wiring an early IBM computer' from the Documenting Science series (1938-58)[reposting from &lt;a class="mention hashtag" href="https://zirk.us/tags/WomensArt" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank"&gt;#&lt;span&gt;WomensArt&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt; at the other place]&lt;br/&gt;&lt;a href="https://files.mastodon.social/cache/media_attachments/files/111/011/011/775/226/816/original/68ccc15b947c0895.jpeg"&gt;&lt;img src="https://files.mastodon.social/cache/media_attachments/files/111/011/011/775/226/816/original/68ccc15b947c0895.jpeg" alt="Mastodon image" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;</description><guid isPermaLink="false">111011675353451732</guid><pubDate>Tue, 05 Sep 2023 08:48:57 +0000</pubDate></item><item><title>Manlio De Domenico</title><link>https://mathstodon.xyz/@manlius/111012039180776854</link><description>It's undeniable that tools like chatGPT are changing (in positive) our society and will have an impact on our lives (at individual level too).However, I can't join the hype for this tool. A lot of people claiming it exhibits ‚Äúemergent features‚Äù, without caring at all that ‚Äúemergence‚Äù has a meaning, and one should prove those claims. Others believe that things like chatGPT are so smart (or going to be soon so smart) that they will be able to destroy us.Well: ask GPT3.5 to bury the ‚Äúsurvivals‚Äù of a plane crash and it will do it.&lt;br/&gt;Ask GPT3.5 to describe the motion of the egg produced by a monkey, and it will be challenged by the problem... even under this custom instruction:‚Äì If you don‚Äôt know how to answer then explicitly mention that it is better for you not to answer since you could not be accurate.&lt;br/&gt;Provide only accurate answers from reliable sources, giving priority to arguments and reasoning that you can support with scientific bibliographic references, such as journal articles, conference proceedings and books ‚ÄìSomeone could tell me that GPT4 would reply differently. Feel free to post a screenshot. And even if it does not, maybe GPT11.5 will make it correctly at the cost of a few 10^16 more parameters, who knows.That's not the point. The point is that this thing is not smart, can't be smart. It's an approximation of a process that we use as a model to approximate how human intelligence works.&lt;a class="mention hashtag" href="https://mathstodon.xyz/tags/GPT" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank"&gt;#&lt;span&gt;GPT&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a class="mention hashtag" href="https://mathstodon.xyz/tags/AI" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank"&gt;#&lt;span&gt;AI&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;a href="https://files.mastodon.social/cache/media_attachments/files/111/012/039/742/763/756/original/7b867dbf3fe653e6.png"&gt;&lt;img src="https://files.mastodon.social/cache/media_attachments/files/111/012/039/742/763/756/original/7b867dbf3fe653e6.png" alt="Mastodon image" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;a href="https://files.mastodon.social/cache/media_attachments/files/111/012/039/812/690/955/original/48fbbee650693134.png"&gt;&lt;img src="https://files.mastodon.social/cache/media_attachments/files/111/012/039/812/690/955/original/48fbbee650693134.png" alt="Mastodon image" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;</description><guid isPermaLink="false">111012039867613749</guid><pubDate>Tue, 05 Sep 2023 10:21:29 +0000</pubDate></item><item><title>Peter Moleman</title><link>https://neuromatch.social/@MolemanPeter/110861691046895058</link><description>&lt;span class="h-card" translate="no"&gt;&lt;a class="u-url mention" href="https://neuromatch.social/@NicoleCRust" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank"&gt;@&lt;span&gt;NicoleCRust&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br/&gt;You may want to read Juarrero, Alicia. Context Changes Everything.&lt;br/&gt;She explains rather convincingly top-down causation in all kinds of systems, including biological, without laws of physics being violated. A deep understanding of complex dynamical systems is the basis. In fact causation is not the central issue, but context independent and context dependent constraints are. The "old school" idea of interventionist causation in fact vanishes! Kendler and Woodward write&lt;br/&gt;" Some external event happened to each individual ([...] which resulted in a major internal change in them which in turn impacted the risk or course of their disorder. [...] Common clinical (and indeed ‚Äòhuman‚Äô) intuition suggests that these changes were causal." But they do not show or prove that this is not by way of changes at the bottom level. (which I do not belief by the way, see our previous discussion of Kendel's 2005 book).&lt;span class="h-card" translate="no"&gt;&lt;a class="u-url mention" href="https://fediscience.org/@DrYohanJohn" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank"&gt;@&lt;span&gt;DrYohanJohn&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="h-card" translate="no"&gt;&lt;a class="u-url mention" href="https://sigmoid.social/@FroehlichMarcel" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank"&gt;@&lt;span&gt;FroehlichMarcel&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="h-card" translate="no"&gt;&lt;a class="u-url mention" href="https://mstdn.social/@WiringtheBrain" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank"&gt;@&lt;span&gt;WiringtheBrain&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;br/&gt;&lt;a class="mention hashtag" href="https://neuromatch.social/tags/neuroscience" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank"&gt;#&lt;span&gt;neuroscience&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;</description><guid isPermaLink="false">111012047543025040</guid><pubDate>Tue, 05 Sep 2023 10:23:36 +0000</pubDate></item><item><title>Earl K. Miller</title><link>https://fediscience.org/@ekmiller/111012332704335308</link><description>Altered age-related alpha and gamma prefrontal-occipital connectivity serving distinct cognitive interference variants&lt;br/&gt;&lt;a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.neuroimage.2023.120351" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank"&gt;&lt;